SIMPLE: jury
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Jury
<hw>Ju"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Etymol.
uncertain.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>For temporary use; -- applied
to a temporary contrivance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Jury rudder</b></col>, <cd>a rudder constructed for
temporary use.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jury</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Jury
<hw>Ju"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Juries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OF. <ets>jur⟦eacute⟧e</ets>
an assize, fr. <ets>jurer</ets> to swear, L. <ets>jurare</ets>,
<ets>jurari</ets>; akin to <ets>jus</ets>, <ets>juris</ets>, right, law.
See <er>Just</er>,<pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Jurat</er>,
<er>Abjure</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A body of people, selected
according to law, impaneled and sworn to inquire into and try any matter
of fact, and to render their true verdict according to the evidence
legally adduced. In criminal trials the number of such persons is
usually twelve, but in civil cases and in grand juries it may different.
See <cref>Grand jury</cref> under <er>Grand</er>, and
<er>Inquest</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>jury</qex>, passing on the prisoner's life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A committee for determining relative merit or
awarding prizes at an exhibition or competition; <as>as, the art
<ex>jury</ex> gave him the first prize</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Jury of inquest</b></col>, <cd>a coroner's jury. See
<er>Inquest</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Juryman</ent>⟦br⟧
